otest, and analyzes the consequences for different classes, sub-regions, and genders. Pomeranz attributes these diverse developments to several causes: the growing but incomplete integration of North China into the world economy, the state's abandonment of many hinterland areas and traditional functions, and the effect of local social structures on these processes. He shows that hinterlands were made, not merely found, and were powerfully shaped by the strategies of local groups as well as outside forces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAsian history. 4aChina. 4aThe Republic. 4achange. 4adynasty. 4aeconomic history. 4aeconomics. 4aeconomy. 4ahistory. 4apolitical history. 4apolitical science. 4asocial history. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aasian history.  abusiness.  achinese history.  achinese republic.  acritical issues.  adifferent classes.  aeast asia.  aecological change.  aecology.  aeconomic development.  aeconomic growth.  aeconomics.  afarming.  afinances.  agoverning.  agovernment.  ahinterland areas.  ainland north china.  alate qing dynasty.  alocal finance.  amodern china.  amodern history.  apopular protests.  asocial change.  asocial issues.  asocial structures.  asociology.  ataxation.  atransportation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520913196?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520913196423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520913196/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles